.TH _ldapfinger 1 "February 1, 2007"
.LO 1

.SH NAME
_ldapfinger \- displays a user/machine/group POSIX account's details.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B _ldapfinger
.RB <username | machinename | groupname | uid | gid>
 
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B <username | machinename | groupname | uid | gid>
The name or id of the user, machine (with an ending $) or group you want to display. You may use a wildcard here to look for substrings. e.g. 'marty*' or '*mart*'.

.SH "SEE ALSO"
ldapscripts(5).

.SH AVAILABILITY
The ldapscripts are provided under the GNU General Public License v2 (see COPYING for more details).
The latest version of the ldapscripts is available on :
.B http://contribs.martymac.com

.SH LIMITATIONS
When used interactively, passwords generated with this command are propagated with the ldappasswd(1) command.
Thus, the resulting format depends on the 'password-hash' option of your server's slapd.conf(5) file.

You can always force an encoded password (using the hash format of your choice) by specifying it on the command line.

.SH BUGS
No bug known.
